<p>Houston's climate demands rigorous HVAC maintenance schedules due to high humidity, frequent storms, and extended operating seasons. Air filters require changing every 30-45 days during peak summer months due to increased runtime and Houston's air quality challenges. Annual professional maintenance should include refrigerant level checks, coil cleaning (essential due to humidity and pollen), electrical connection inspection, and drainage system cleaning to prevent the mold and algae growth common in humid climates. After major storms‚Äîfrequent in Houston‚Äîhave systems inspected for hail damage, electrical issues, and debris accumulation. Many Houston contractors offer maintenance plans (\$150-300 annually) that include bi-annual tune-ups, priority service, and discounts on repairs, providing valuable peace of mind given the critical nature of cooling systems in this climate.</p>

